Your new framing is mostly right, but I would sharpen it:

The surviving mechanism is not “D3D11 context calls race” in the naive sense. It is “engine-level graphics transactions race while D3D11 serializes only individual COM calls.”

That distinction matters. The D3D11 multithread lock makes `Map`, `Unmap`, `PSSetShaderResources`, `DrawIndexed`, etc. individually thread-safe. It does not make this atomic:

```text
thread A: set VB/IB/constants/SRVs for terrain LOD draw
thread B: set/update VB/IB/SRVs for another object or loader path
thread A: DrawIndexed
```

RenderDoc would replay the recorded ordering exactly, but if capture instrumentation changes scheduling, the bad interleaving may never enter the capture.

**Most suspicious concrete producer**

The dynamic VB/IB rings are the first place I would attack.

In this tree they are process-wide shared rings with unsynchronized static state:

- [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:37): `ms_newFrame`, `ms_used`, shared `ms_d3dRingBuffer`
- [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:199): `lock()` computes/reserves a slice, maps the shared buffer, returns a CPU pointer
- [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:241): `m_offset` is derived from global `ms_used`
- [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:244): `ms_used += length`
- [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:312): `unlock()` unmaps the shared ring

Same issue exists for the dynamic IB ring:

- [Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp:25)
- [Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp:157)
- [Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp:194)

That is not protected by the D3D11 runtime. The runtime lock does not protect `ms_used`, `ms_newFrame`, `m_offset`, returned mapped pointers, or “lock/write/unlock/draw” as one logical operation. RenderDoc slowing down submission could absolutely hide this.

This also fits “geometry shards” better than the mip theory did. Wrong textures and terrain colors can come along for the ride if state-cache application interleaves too, but shards point hard at VB/IB data or offsets.

**Do not use a per-call global D3D lock as the decisive test**

A global lock around every `ID3D11DeviceContext` call mostly duplicates the runtime’s multithread protection. It might change timing enough to mask the bug, but it will not prove much.

The decisive test is stronger:

Add a debug-only **graphics transaction owner guard** around every D3D11 plugin entrypoint that can touch GPU state or GPU resources, and fail/log if it runs off the render thread or concurrently.

Concretely:

```text
begin graphics API entry:
  assert current thread == render thread
  or take one global recursive GraphicsD3D11CriticalSection

cover:
  resource create
  texture/VB/IB lock + unlock
  StateCache apply
  Set* calls
  Draw/DrawIndexed
  Present
```

Best version: do not just lock per COM call. Lock from `lock()` through `unlock()` for VB/IB/texture paths, and lock the whole state-apply + draw path. If corruption disappears, the bug is confirmed as an engine-level transaction race. If it remains unchanged, timing becomes much less likely.

Even better diagnostic: first make it **assert/log only**:

```text
thread id, operation, resource pointer, lock/unlock/draw, frame number
```

If you see any D3D11 resource lock/update/draw from a non-render thread, you have a smoking gun.

**Why D3D9 could tolerate this**

D3D9 likely got accidental serialization and different resource semantics:

- D3D9 managed/default pool behavior hides some update timing.
- D3D9 `Lock` paths may allocate/rename/stall differently.
- The old renderer may have been used by the engine under assumptions that happened to work with D3D9’s coarse driver behavior.
- D3D11 `Map(WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE)` is a promise from the app. If your shared ring offset accounting races, the app is promising “I won’t overwrite in-flight data” while doing exactly that.

**On RenderDoc replay-clean**

Yes, replay-clean is still consistent with an intermittent capturable bug if you have not captured a frame that was definitely corrupt at the presented backbuffer. “During a corrupt roam” is not enough.

Next capture-side discriminator:

1. Find a latched-corrupt surface.
2. Start capture while staring at it for several seconds.
3. Export the captured Present backbuffer.
4. Also take an immediate non-RenderDoc screenshot/video frame of the same visible frame if possible.

If latched corruption survives live but every captured Present is clean, capture instrumentation is masking the producer. If you ever capture the latched-corrupt backbuffer and replay is corrupt, it is in-stream and you should use pixel history/resource inspection.

An even cleaner non-RenderDoc test is an internal pre-Present backbuffer readback: `CopyResource` swapchain backbuffer to staging immediately before `Present`, save PNG/hash. If the internal backbuffer is corrupt when the screen is corrupt, it is renderer/resource/state. If internal is clean but the display is corrupt, then look at swapchain/compositor/driver/MPO. Given your symptoms, I would expect internal readback to be corrupt only when RenderDoc is not attached.

**Non-timing alternatives worth not ignoring**

Present/compositor is possible only if the exact pre-Present backbuffer is clean while the monitor/screenshot is corrupt. The surface-specific wrong textures and geometry shards make that unlikely, but the internal readback test kills it fast.

Baked render target/depth issues are also lower probability. RenderDoc would usually replay those if they affected the captured backbuffer. They become plausible only if the badness is produced by live-only resource updates outside the captured frame or by capture changing initialization/order.

My single next test: **debug transaction guard + render-thread assertion over D3D11 plugin entrypoints**, especially dynamic VB/IB lock/unlock and state-apply/draw. That tests the actual hole the runtime lock does not cover.
